Class: http://ontology.dumontierlab.com/PeriodElement

Label: Period element

Description: An element of a horizontal row of the periodic table that shares the same number of electron shells. Each shell is divided into different subshells, which as atomic number increases are filled in roughly this order: 1s 2s 2p 3s 3p 4s 3d 4p 5s 4d 5p 6s 4f 5d 6p 7s 5f 6d 7p 8s 5g 6f 7d 8p

Has Super Class (direct): http://ontology.dumontierlab.com/PeriodicTableElement

Has Super Class (all): http://ontology.dumontierlab.com/PeriodicTableElement | http://ontology.dumontierlab.com/Element | http://ontology.dumontierlab.com/PureSubstance | http://ontology.dumontierlab.com/ChemicalSubstance | http://www.ifomis.org/bfo/1.0/snap#Object | http://www.ifomis.org/bfo/1.0/snap#IndependentContinuant | http://www.ifomis.org/bfo/1.0/snap#Continuant | http://www.ifomis.org/bfo/1.0#Entity

Has Sub Class (direct): http://ontology.dumontierlab.com/Period1Element | http://ontology.dumontierlab.com/Period2Element | http://ontology.dumontierlab.com/Period3Element | http://ontology.dumontierlab.com/Period4Element | http://ontology.dumontierlab.com/Period5Element | http://ontology.dumontierlab.com/Period6Element | http://ontology.dumontierlab.com/Period7Element

Implementation: 
@prefix owl: <http://www.w3.org/2002/07/owl#> .
@prefix rdf: <http://www.w3.org/1999/02/22-rdf-syntax-ns#> .
@prefix rdfs: <http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#> .
@prefix xsd: <http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#> .

<http://ontology.dumontierlab.com/PeriodElement> a owl:Class ;
    rdfs:label "period element" ;
    rdfs:comment """An element of a horizontal row of the periodic table that shares the same number of electron shells. Each shell is divided into different subshells, which as atomic number increases are filled in roughly this order:

1s 
2s           2p  
3s           3p  
4s        3d 4p  
5s        4d 5p
6s     4f 5d 6p  
7s     5f 6d 7p  
8s  5g 6f 7d 8p"""^^xsd:string ;
    rdfs:subClassOf <http://ontology.dumontierlab.com/PeriodicTableElement> ;
    owl:equivalentClass [ a owl:Class ;
            owl:unionOf ( <http://ontology.dumontierlab.com/Period1Element> <http://ontology.dumontierlab.com/Period2Element> <http://ontology.dumontierlab.com/Period3Element> <http://ontology.dumontierlab.com/Period4Element> <http://ontology.dumontierlab.com/Period5Element> <http://ontology.dumontierlab.com/Period6Element> <http://ontology.dumontierlab.com/Period7Element> ) ] .

Class: http://ontology.dumontierlab.com/SIsomer

Class: http://www.ifomis.org/bfo/1.0/snap#Continuant

Label: Continuant

Description: Synonyms: endurant - Examples: a heart, a person, the color of a tomato, the mass of a cloud, a symphony orchestra, the disposition of blood to coagulate, the lawn and atmosphere in front of our building - Definition: An entity that exists in full at any time in which it exists at all, persists through time while maintaining its identity and has no temporal parts.

<http://www.ifomis.org/bfo/1.0/snap#Continuant> a owl:Class ;
    rdfs:label "continuant"^^xsd:string ;
    rdfs:comment "Definition: An entity that exists in full at any time in which it exists at all, persists through time while maintaining its identity and has no temporal parts."^^xsd:string,
        "Examples: a heart, a person, the color of a tomato, the mass of a cloud, a symphony orchestra, the disposition of blood to coagulate, the lawn and atmosphere in front of our building"^^xsd:string,
        "Synonyms: endurant"^^xsd:string ;
    rdfs:subClassOf <http://www.ifomis.org/bfo/1.0#Entity> ;
    owl:disjointWith <http://www.ifomis.org/bfo/1.0/span#Occurrent> ;
    owl:equivalentClass [ a owl:Class ;
            owl:unionOf ( <http://www.ifomis.org/bfo/1.0/snap#DependentContinuant> <http://www.ifomis.org/bfo/1.0/snap#IndependentContinuant> <http://www.ifomis.org/bfo/1.0/snap#SpatialRegion> ) ] .

Class: http://www.ifomis.org/bfo/1.0/snap#DependentContinuant

Label: Dependent_continuant

Description: Synonyms: property, trope, mode - Examples: the mass of a cloud, the smell of mozzarella, the liquidity of blood, the color of a tomato, the disposition of fish to decay, the role of being a doctor, the function of the heart to pump blood - Definition: A continuant that inheres in or is borne by other entities.

<http://www.ifomis.org/bfo/1.0/snap#DependentContinuant> a owl:Class ;
    rdfs:label "dependent_continuant"^^xsd:string ;
    rdfs:comment "Definition: A continuant that inheres in or is borne by other entities."^^xsd:string,
        "Examples: the mass of a cloud, the smell of mozzarella, the liquidity of blood, the color of a tomato, the disposition of fish to decay, the role of being a doctor, the function of the heart to pump blood"^^xsd:string,
        "Synonyms: property, trope, mode"^^xsd:string ;
    rdfs:subClassOf <http://www.ifomis.org/bfo/1.0/snap#Continuant> ;
    owl:disjointWith <http://www.ifomis.org/bfo/1.0/snap#IndependentContinuant>,
        <http://www.ifomis.org/bfo/1.0/snap#SpatialRegion> ;
    owl:equivalentClass [ a owl:Class ;
            owl:unionOf ( <http://www.ifomis.org/bfo/1.0/snap#Quality> <http://www.ifomis.org/bfo/1.0/snap#RealizableEntity> ) ] .

Class: http://www.ifomis.org/bfo/1.0/snap#Disposition

Label: Disposition

Description: Definition: A realizable entity that essentially causes a specific process or transformation in the object in which it inheres, under specific circumstances and in conjunction with the laws of nature. A general formula for dispositions is: X (object) has the disposition D to (transform, initiate a process) R under conditions C. - Examples: the disposition of vegetables to decay when not refrigerated, the disposition of a vase to brake if dropped, the disposition of blood to coagulate, the disposition of a patient with a weakened immune system to contract disease, the disposition of metal to conduct electricity.

Has Super Class (direct): http://www.ifomis.org/bfo/1.0/snap#RealizableEntity

Has Super Class (all): http://www.ifomis.org/bfo/1.0/snap#RealizableEntity | http://www.ifomis.org/bfo/1.0/snap#DependentContinuant | http://www.ifomis.org/bfo/1.0/snap#Continuant | http://www.ifomis.org/bfo/1.0#Entity

Description: Examples: upper and lower lobes of the left lung, the dorsal and ventral surfaces of the body, the east side of Saarbruecken, the lower right portion of a human torso - Synonyms: fiat substance part - Definition: An independent continuant that is part of an object but is not demarcated by any physical discontinuities.

Class: http://www.ifomis.org/bfo/1.0/snap#Function

Label: Function

Description: Definition: A realizable entity the manifestation of which is an essentialy end-directed activity of a continuant entity in virtue of that continuant entity being a specific kind of entity in the kind or kinds of contexts that it is made for. - Examples: the function of a birth canal to enable transport, the function of the heart in the body to pump blood, the function of reproduction in the transmission of genetic material, the digestive function of the stomach to nutriate the body, the function of a hammer to drive in nails, the function of a computer program to compute mathematical equations, the function of an automobile to provide transportation, the function of a judge in a court of law

Class: http://www.ifomis.org/bfo/1.0/snap#IndependentContinuant

Label: Independent_continuant

Description: Definition: A continuant that is a bearer of qualities and realizable entities, in which other entities inhere and which itself cannot inhere in anything. - Synonyms: substantial entity - Examples: an organism, a heart, a leg, a person, a symphony orchestra, a chair, the bottom right portion of a human torso, the lawn and atmosphere in front of our building

<http://www.ifomis.org/bfo/1.0/snap#IndependentContinuant> a owl:Class ;
    rdfs:label "independent_continuant"^^xsd:string ;
    rdfs:comment "Definition: A continuant that is a bearer of qualities and realizable entities, in which other entities inhere and which itself cannot inhere in anything."^^xsd:string,
        "Examples: an organism, a heart, a leg, a person, a symphony orchestra, a chair, the bottom right portion of a human torso, the lawn and atmosphere in front of our building"^^xsd:string,
        "Synonyms: substantial entity"^^xsd:string ;
    rdfs:subClassOf <http://www.ifomis.org/bfo/1.0/snap#Continuant> ;
    owl:disjointWith <http://www.ifomis.org/bfo/1.0/snap#SpatialRegion> ;
    owl:equivalentClass [ a owl:Class ;
            owl:unionOf ( <http://www.ifomis.org/bfo/1.0/snap#FiatObjectPart> <http://www.ifomis.org/bfo/1.0/snap#Object> <http://www.ifomis.org/bfo/1.0/snap#ObjectAggregate> <http://www.ifomis.org/bfo/1.0/snap#ObjectBoundary> <http://www.ifomis.org/bfo/1.0/snap#Site> ) ] .

Class: http://www.ifomis.org/bfo/1.0/snap#Object

Label: Object

Description: Examples: an organism, a heart, a chair, a lung, an apple - Synonyms: substance - Definition: A independent continuant that is spatially extended, maximally self-connected and self-contained (the parts of a substance are not separated from each other by spatial gaps) and possesses an internal unity. The identity of substantial objects is independent of that of other entities and can be maintained through time and through loss and gain of parts and qualities.

Has Super Class (direct): http://www.ifomis.org/bfo/1.0/snap#IndependentContinuant

@prefix owl: <http://www.w3.org/2002/07/owl#> .
@prefix rdfs: <http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#> .
@prefix xsd: <http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#> .

<http://www.ifomis.org/bfo/1.0/snap#Object> a owl:Class ;
    rdfs:label "object"^^xsd:string ;
    rdfs:comment "Definition: A independent continuant that is spatially extended, maximally self-connected and self-contained (the parts of a substance are not separated from each other by spatial gaps) and possesses an internal unity. The identity of substantial objects is independent of that of other entities and can be maintained through time and through loss and gain of parts and qualities."^^xsd:string,
        "Examples: an organism, a heart, a chair, a lung, an apple"^^xsd:string,
        "Synonyms: substance"^^xsd:string ;
    rdfs:subClassOf <http://www.ifomis.org/bfo/1.0/snap#IndependentContinuant> ;
    owl:disjointWith <http://www.ifomis.org/bfo/1.0/snap#ObjectAggregate>,
        <http://www.ifomis.org/bfo/1.0/snap#ObjectBoundary>,
        <http://www.ifomis.org/bfo/1.0/snap#Site> .

Class: http://www.ifomis.org/bfo/1.0/snap#ObjectAggregate

Label: Object_aggregate

Description: Definition: An independent continuant that is a mereological sum of separate objects and possesses non-connected boundaries. - Synonyms: substance aggregate - Examples: a heap of stones, a group of commuters on the subway, a collection of random bacteria, a flock of geese, the patients in a hospital

Class: http://www.ifomis.org/bfo/1.0/snap#ObjectBoundary

Label: Object_boundary

Description: Definition: An independent continuant that is a lower dimensional part of a spatial entity, normally a closed two-dimensional surface. Boundaries are those privileged parts of objects that exist at exactly the point where the object is separated off from the rest of the existing entities in the world. - Examples: the surface of the skin, the surface of the earth, the surface of the interior of the stomach, the outer surface of a cell or cell wall - Synonyms: substance boundary - Comment: Boundaries are theoretically difficult entities to account for, however the intuitive notion of a physical boundary as a surface of some sort (whether inside or outside of a thing) will generally serve as a good guide for the use of this universal.

Has Super Class (direct): http://www.ifomis.org/bfo/1.0/snap#IndependentContinuant

Has Super Class (all): http://www.ifomis.org/bfo/1.0/snap#IndependentContinuant | http://www.ifomis.org/bfo/1.0/snap#Continuant | http://www.ifomis.org/bfo/1.0#Entity

Class: http://www.ifomis.org/bfo/1.0/snap#RealizableEntity

Label: Realizable_entity

Description: Definition: A dependent continuant that inheres in continuants and are not exhibited in full at every time in which it inheres in an entity or group of entities. The exhibition or actualization of a realizable entity is a particular manifestation, functioning or process that occurs under certain circumstances. - Examples: the role of being a doctor, the function of the reproductive organs, the disposition of blood to coagulate, the disposition of metal to conduct electricity

Class: http://www.ifomis.org/bfo/1.0/snap#Role

Label: Role

Description: Examples: the role of a person as a surgeon, the role of an artificial heart in pumping blood, the role of a chemical compound in an experiment, the role of a drug in the treatment of a disease, the role of a patient relative as defined by a hospital administrative form, the role of a woman as a legal mother in the context of system of laws, the role of a biological grandfather as legal guardian in the context of a system of laws, the role of a tree in maintaining stability in an ecosystem, the role of ingested matter in digestion - Definition: A realizable entity the manifestation of which brings about some result or end that is not essential to a continuant in virtue of the kind of thing that it is but that can be served or participated in by that kind of continuant in some kinds of natural, social or institutional contexts.

Class: http://www.ifomis.org/bfo/1.0/snap#Site

Label: Site

Description: Comment: Sites should not be confused with spatial regions. Sites characteristically have a filling or medium and are capable of altering their spatial location (moving from one spatial region to another) without altering their identity. - Definition: An independent continuant consisting of a characteristic spatial shape in relation to some arrangement of other continuants and of the medium which is enclosed in whole or in part by this characteristic spatial shape. Sites are entities that can be occupied by other continuants. - Examples: a city, a nasal cavity, a blood vein, an environment, sinuses, canals, ventricles, the lumen of the gastrointestinal tract, the location of the battle of Austerlitz, the interior of the aorta, the room in which one is located, the top of one's desk including the things that are on it and the atmosphere surrounding them.

Class: http://www.ifomis.org/bfo/1.0/snap#SpatialRegion

Label: Spatial_region

Description: Definition: An independent continuant that is neither bearer of qualities nor inheres in any other entities. - Examples: the sum total of all space in the universe, parts of the sum total of all space in the universe - Comment: Spatial regions should not be confused with sites. Spatial regions exist as parts of pure or absolute space, have a dimensionality and a shape but require no filling in order to exist and are also immobile.

Class: http://www.ifomis.org/bfo/1.0/span#ProcessualContext

Label: Processual_context

Description: Comment: setting - Definition: An occurrent consisting of a characteristic spatial shape inhering in some arrangement of other occurrents. Processual contexts are characteristically entities at or in which other occurrents can be located or occur. - Examples: a surgical operation as processual context for a nosocomical infection, a routine check-up as processual context for the finding of a tumor, a clinical trial as processual context for the discovery of a new treatment or drug

Class: http://www.ifomis.org/bfo/1.0/span#SpatiotemporalRegion

Label: Spatiotemporal_region

Description: Definition: An occurrent at or in which processual entities can be located. - Comment: This is the time and space within which occurrents exist. Occurrents exist in space and time in a different way from that in which continuants do and thus the space and time in which they exist is itself different. Spatiotemporal region's importance is primarily theoretical and it will not be used often in most domain ontology applications. - Examples: the spatiotemporal region occupied by a human life, the spatiotemporal region occupied by the development of a cancer tumor, the spatiotemporal context occupied by a process of cellular meiosis

Has Super Class (direct): http://www.ifomis.org/bfo/1.0/span#Occurrent

Class: matonto:GrainSize

Label: Grain size

Description: Grain size refers to the diameter of individual grains of sediment, or the lithified particles in clastic rocks. The term may also be applied to other granular materials. This is different from the crystallite size, which is the size of a single crystal inside the particles or grains. A single grain can be composed of several crystals. Granular material can range from very small colloidal particles, through clay, silt, sand, and gravel, to boulders.

Description: a macroscopic region defined by boundaries that determine processes which are allowed to affect the interior of the region

Has Super Class (direct): http://www.ifomis.org/bfo/1.0/snap#ThreeDimensionalRegion

Has Super Class (all): http://www.ifomis.org/bfo/1.0/snap#ThreeDimensionalRegion | http://www.ifomis.org/bfo/1.0/snap#SpatialRegion | http://www.ifomis.org/bfo/1.0/snap#Continuant | http://www.ifomis.org/bfo/1.0#Entity

Has Sub Class (direct): matonto:ClosedThermodynamicSystem | matonto:IsolatedThermodynamicSystem | matonto:OpenThermodynamicSystem

Implementation: 
@prefix : <http://matonto.org/ontologies/matonto#> .
@prefix owl: <http://www.w3.org/2002/07/owl#> .
@prefix rdfs: <http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#> .

    rdfs:label "thermodynamic system" ;
    rdfs:comment "a macroscopic region defined by boundaries that determine processes which are allowed to affect the interior of the region" ;
    rdfs:subClassOf <http://www.ifomis.org/bfo/1.0/snap#ThreeDimensionalRegion> .

Class: matonto:UltimateTensileStrength

Label: Ultimate tensile strength

Has Super Class (direct): http://ontology.dumontierlab.com/MeasuredProperty

Has Super Class (all): http://ontology.dumontierlab.com/MeasuredProperty | http://www.ifomis.org/bfo/1.0/snap#Quality | http://www.ifomis.org/bfo/1.0/snap#DependentContinuant | http://www.ifomis.org/bfo/1.0/snap#Continuant | http://www.ifomis.org/bfo/1.0#Entity

Implementation: 
@prefix : <http://matonto.org/ontologies/matonto#> .
@prefix owl: <http://www.w3.org/2002/07/owl#> .
@prefix rdfs: <http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#> .
@prefix skos: <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#> .

:UltimateTensileStrength a owl:Class ;
    rdfs:label "ultimate tensile strength" ;
    rdfs:comment "Ultimate tensile strength is the maximum stress that a material can withstand while being stretched or pulled before failing or breaking." ;
    rdfs:subClassOf [ a owl:Restriction ;
            owl:allValuesFrom <http://ontology.dumontierlab.com/PressureUnit> ;

        [ a owl:Restriction ;
            owl:onProperty <http://ontology.dumontierlab.com/hasUnit> ;
            owl:someValuesFrom <http://ontology.dumontierlab.com/PressureUnit> ],
        <http://ontology.dumontierlab.com/MeasuredProperty> ;
    skos:altLabel "TS",
        "UTS",
        "tensile strength",
        "ultimate strength" .

Class: matonto:YoungsModulus

Label: Youngs modulus

Description: Young's modulus is a measure of the stiffness of an elastic isotropic material and is a quantity used to characterize materials. It is defined as the ratio of the stress along an axis over the strain along that axis in the range of stress in which Hooke's law holds.

Has Super Class (direct): matonto:ElasticModulus

Has Super Class (all): matonto:ElasticModulus | http://ontology.dumontierlab.com/MeasuredProperty | http://www.ifomis.org/bfo/1.0/snap#Quality | http://www.ifomis.org/bfo/1.0/snap#DependentContinuant | http://www.ifomis.org/bfo/1.0/snap#Continuant | http://www.ifomis.org/bfo/1.0#Entity

Implementation: 
@prefix : <http://matonto.org/ontologies/matonto#> .
@prefix owl: <http://www.w3.org/2002/07/owl#> .
@prefix rdfs: <http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#> .
@prefix skos: <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#> .

:YoungsModulus a owl:Class,
        owl:NamedIndividual ;
    rdfs:label "youngs modulus" ;
    :hasCommonSymbol "E" ;
    rdfs:comment "Young's modulus is a measure of the stiffness of an elastic isotropic material and is a quantity used to characterize materials. It is defined as the ratio of the stress along an axis over the strain along that axis in the range of stress in which Hooke's law holds." ;
    rdfs:subClassOf :ElasticModulus ;
    skos:altLabel "Young's modulus",
        "tensile modulus" .
